`public init(dynamicProvider: @escaping (UITraitCollection) -&gt; UIColor) `


It is used as follows and will ensure the UI is updated whenever the mode is changed:

    extension UIColor {
    	static var customColor: UIColor {
    		if #available(iOS 13, *) {
    			return UIColor { (traitCollection: UITraitCollection) -&gt; UIColor in
    				if traitCollection.userInterfaceStyle == .dark {
    					return .black
    				} else {
    					return .white
    				}
    			}
    		} else {
    			return .white
    		}
    	}
    }

I would now like to be able to not just support .dark/.light, but custom values. Like for defining colors for different themes, while also using this very convenient way of reacting to changes.

Is there a good way to access custom params inside of this closure?

**Considered Options:** 

1. Access UserDefaults inside of the block to check the current used theme. -&gt; Would trigger a lot of requests to UserDefaults when TraitCollection changed.

2. Access singleton inside of the block to cache the current used theme. -&gt; Better performance, but for the cost of introducing a singleton.

3. Change from static var of UIColor to a custom color provider used everywhere to get the correct color. -&gt; Big impact on all UI code.


Is there an easier way I am missing here?

